# Spec file format

These rules apply whenever you read or edit any file under `specs/`.
They enforce the Kiro-style structure that the orchestrator in
`spec-sessions.mdc` produces.

## Filenames are fixed

Inside `specs/<feature-name>/`, only these filenames are allowed:

- `requirements.md` — feature spec (Phase 1)
- `bugfix.md` — bug spec (replaces `requirements.md` for bugfix mode)
- `design.md` — technical design (Phase 2)
- `tasks.md` — implementation plan (Phase 3)
- `notes.md` — optional running notes during implementation
- `decisions.md` — optional ADR-style records of decisions made
  while building the feature; rolls up into project-level
  `DECISIONS.md` at completion.

Do not invent new filenames. Do not put spec content at the project
root or under any other directory.

## requirements.md — EARS only

Every acceptance criterion in `requirements.md` MUST use one of the
five EARS patterns:

| Pattern | Form |
|------------------|----------------------------------------------------------|
| Ubiquitous | `THE SYSTEM SHALL <action>.` |
| Event-driven | `WHEN <trigger> THE SYSTEM SHALL <action>.` |
| State-driven | `WHILE <state> THE SYSTEM SHALL <action>.` |
| Conditional | `IF <condition> THEN THE SYSTEM SHALL <action>.` |
| Contextual | `WHERE <context> THE SYSTEM SHALL <action>.` |

Reject criteria like *"the system should be fast"* or *"the system
must be user-friendly"* — they are not EARS and not testable.

Each requirement is a numbered top-level section
(`### Requirement 1: <title>`) and contains:

1. A `**User Story:** As a <role>, I want <functionality>, so that
   <benefit>.` line.
2. A numbered `#### Acceptance Criteria` list.
3. A `#### Additional Details` block with priority, complexity,
   dependencies, assumptions.

## design.md — sections required

`design.md` must contain at minimum:

- `## Overview` (with design goals + key decisions)
- `## Architecture` (with at least one mermaid diagram for any
  feature that touches more than two modules)
- `## Components and Interfaces` (one subsection per component;
  each lists Purpose / Responsibilities / Interfaces / Implementation
  notes)
- `## Data Models` (typed schema or pydantic model sketch)
- `## API Design` (if the feature exposes any interface — REST,
  CLI, websocket, queue, internal Python API)
- `## Error Handling` (categorized errors; module-specific
  exceptions per `coding-standards.mdc`)
- `## Testing Strategy` (unit / integration / e2e split)
- `## Security Considerations` (per `security.mdc`)
- `## Performance Considerations` (latency / throughput / cost)

Every component description should cite the requirement numbers it
fulfills, e.g. *"satisfies Requirement 1.2, 3.1"*.

## tasks.md — two-level checklist with traceability

`tasks.md` is a markdown checklist. The structure is **strictly
two-level**:

```markdown
- [ ] 1. <Top-level epic / phase>
- [ ] 1.1 <Specific implementation task>
  - <implementation detail>
  - <files / functions to create or modify>
  - <testing expectation>
  - _Requirements: 1.2, 3.1_
- [ ] 1.2 <Next specific task>
  - …
  - _Requirements: 2.1_
```

Hard rules:

- **No third-level nesting.** Use `1.1`, `1.2`, …, `2.1`, never `1.1.1`.
- Every leaf task ends with `_Requirements: <comma-separated ids>_`
  pointing back to numbered acceptance criteria in `requirements.md`
  (or sections in `bugfix.md`).
- Each leaf task must be doable in 1–4 hours and produce testable code.
- A test task may be a peer of an implementation task, or merged into
  the same task as a sub-bullet — never deferred to the end.
- Forbidden tasks: vague ones (*"make it better"*), non-coding
  ones (*"deploy to production"*, *"get user feedback"*),
  monolithic ones (*"implement the whole feature"*).

Use checkbox states:

- `- [ ]` not started
- `- [~]` in progress (optional convention)
- `- [x]` complete

Task IDs (`1.1`, `1.2`, …) are stable once written. Do not renumber
tasks after the spec is approved; if scope grows, append (`1.5`, `1.6`).

## bugfix.md — required sections

A bug spec replaces `requirements.md` for bugfix-mode sessions. It
must contain:

- `## Summary` — one sentence
- `## Current Behavior` — what happens now (cite logs, traces,
  screenshots if relevant)
- `## Expected Behavior` — what should happen, in EARS form
- `## Reproduction Steps` — minimal repro
- `## Root Cause Hypothesis` — best current theory
- `## Behavior That Must NOT Change` — explicit anti-regressions
- `## Affected Files / Modules` — scope estimate

`design.md` and `tasks.md` for bugfixes follow the same rules as
above, except `tasks.md` MUST include at least one regression-test
task that fails before the fix and passes after.

## Cross-phase consistency

When you edit any spec file, check the others in the same folder:

- A new requirement → either covered by an existing component in
  `design.md` or design.md must be updated.
- A new component in `design.md` → at least one task in `tasks.md`
  must implement it.
- A new task in `tasks.md` → its `_Requirements:` ids must exist
  in `requirements.md` or `bugfix.md`.

If a change makes the three documents inconsistent, fix the
inconsistency before moving on. The spec is a contract between phases.
